Top 10 Matches

liza mladentseva

2025-03-19

Introduction

This project explores a professional tennis match dataset sourced from Kaggle - ATP Matches. The dataset contains detailed information about tennis matches, including match results, player names, surfaces, rankings, and match statistics.

My goal is to investigate Federers and Nadals performance over time, their results on different surfaces, and match patterns against their top rivals. I will explore this using data wrangling, visualizations, and statistical analysis in R.

Dataset Overview

  • Rows (matches): The dataset contains over 9,000 match records.
  • Players: It includes professional ATP players, with both winners and losers recorded.
  • Time span: The matches span from 1978 to 2024.
  • Key variables include:
    • winner_name, loser_name: Players involved
    • surface: Surface type (Clay, Grass, Hard)
    • tourney_level: Type of tournament (Grand Slam, Masters, etc.)
    • winner_rank, loser_rank: ATP rankings of players
    • w_ace, l_ace: Number of aces served by each player
    • minutes: Duration of the match

This dataset is suitable for performance analysis, trends, and comparisons.

Variable Classification

  • Binary: Win (logical values, typically representing True/False)
  • Nominal: PlayerName (categories of names), GameType (categories without order), Country (names of countries)
  • Ordinal: Rank (ranking in a game, has a meaningful order)
  • Discrete: MatchID (countable, unique identifiers for each match), Score (countable points in a game), Age (countable, number of years)
  • Continuous: PlayDuration (duration in hours or minutes, can take any value within a range), Temperature (measured in degrees, can take any continuous value)

Three questions that you could potentially answer with your dataset.

Performance Over Time Examines how Federers win rate evolved throughout his career, identifying peaks and declines by comparing matches won vs.played each year.

Surface Analysis Determines Federers best court surface (clay, grass, or hard) by analyzing win rates, scores, and titles, revealing where he has the most advantage.

Opponent Comparison Evaluates Federers head-to-head records against top rivals (Nadal, Djokovic, Murray), analyzing win rates, match outcomes, and possible age-related impacts.

Including Plots

Win Rate by Surface

federer_matches <- matches %>%
  filter(grepl("Roger Federer", winner_name) | grepl("Roger Federer", loser_name)) %>%
  mutate(federer_won = (winner_name == "Roger Federer"))

surface_data <- federer_matches %>%
  group_by(surface) %>%
  summarise(WinRate = mean(federer_won) * 100, .groups = 'drop')

ggplot(surface_data, aes(x = surface, y = WinRate, fill = surface)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(WinRate, 1), "%")), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(
    title = "Federer's Win Rate by Surface",
    x = "Surface Type",
    y = "Win Rate (%)" 
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Federers strongest surface is Grass, where he has the highest win rate, followed by Hard courts. His win rate is slightly lower on Clay, which aligns with known career performance patterns.

Win Rate by Tournament Level

tournament_stats <- federer_matches %>%
  group_by(TournamentLevel = tourney_level) %>%
  summarise(Wins = sum(winner_name == "Roger Federer"), 
            Matches = n(), 
            WinRate = Wins / Matches * 100, .groups = 'drop')

ggplot(tournament_stats, aes(x = reorder(TournamentLevel, -WinRate), y = WinRate, fill = TournamentLevel)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black", width = 0.8) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(WinRate, 1), "%")), vjust = -0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("F" = "red", "M" = "blue", "A" = "green", "D" = "purple", "G" = "gold")) +
  labs(
    title = "Federer's Win Rate by Tournament Level",
    x = "Tournament Level (A, M, G, etc.)",
    y = "Win Rate (%)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 12)) +
  ylim(0, 100)

Federer performs consistently well in Grand Slam (G) and ATP 500 (A) tournaments, showing a high level of performance under pressure. Win rate dips slightly at the Masters 1000 (M) level, possibly due to stronger competition.

Win Percentage and Losers Rank

matches <- matches %>%
  mutate(win_percentage = ifelse(winner_name == "Roger Federer", 1, 0))

ggplot(matches, aes(x = loser_rank, y = win_percentage)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "blue") +  # Add scatter points
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +  # Add regression line
  labs(title = "Win Percentage vs. Opponent's Ranking",
       x = "Opponent's Ranking",

Correlation Analysis

player_name <- "Rafael Nadal"

df <- matches %>%
  mutate(win_percentage = as.numeric(winner_name == player_name))

correlation <- cor(df$win_percentage, df$loser_rank, use = "complete.obs")

print(paste("Correlation between win percentage and opponent's ranking:", round(correlation, 5)))
## [1] "Correlation between win percentage and opponent's ranking: 0.00296"
if (correlation > 0) {
  print("There is a positive correlation between win percentage and opponent's ranking.")
  print("This suggests that as the opponent's ranking increases, the player's win percentage also tends to increase.")
} else if (correlation < 0) {
  print("There is a negative correlation between win percentage and opponent's ranking.")
  print("This suggests that as the opponent's ranking increases, the player's win percentage tends to decrease.")
} else {
  print("There is no linear correlation between win percentage and opponent's ranking.")
}
## [1] "There is a positive correlation between win percentage and opponent's ranking."
## [1] "This suggests that as the opponent's ranking increases, the player's win percentage also tends to increase."

Correlation between win percentage and opponents ranking: 0.00296 There is a positive correlation between win percentage and opponents ranking. As the opponents ranking increases, the players win percentage also tends to increase.

Win Rate by Aces

aces_summary <- matches %>%
  summarise(aces_winning = mean(w_ace, na.rm = TRUE),
            aces_losing = mean(l_ace, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(aces_winning, aces_losing), names_to = "MatchType", values_to = "Aces")

ggplot(aces_summary, aes(x = MatchType, y = Aces, fill = MatchType)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "black") +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(Aces, 1)), vjust = -0.5, size = 5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("aces_winning" = "green", "aces_losing" = "red")) +
  labs(title = "Average Aces in Winning vs Losing Matches",
       x = "Match Outcome",
       y = "Average Aces",
       caption = "Data Source: Tennis Dataset") +
  theme_minimal()

Nadal tends to serve more aces in winning matches compared to losing ones, indicating that strong serving is a key factor in his victories.

T-test

aces_winning <- matches %>%
  filter(!is.na(w_ace)) %>%
  pull(w_ace)

aces_losing <- matches %>%
  filter(!is.na(l_ace)) %>%
  pull(l_ace)

t_test_result <- t.test(aces_winning, aces_losing, var.equal = FALSE)

print(paste("T-statistic:", round(t_test_result$statistic, 5)))
## [1] "T-statistic: 19.27055"
print(paste("P-value:", round(t_test_result$p.value, 5)))
## [1] "P-value: 0"
if (t_test_result$p.value < 0.05) {
  print("There is a statistically significant difference in the average number of aces between winning and losing matches.")
} else {
  print("There is no statistically significant difference in the average number of aces between winning and losing matches.")
}
## [1] "There is a statistically significant difference in the average number of aces between winning and losing matches."

Mutate

library(dplyr)

matches <- matches %>%
  mutate(win_percentage = (winner_rank / (winner_rank + loser_rank)) * 100)
matches <- matches %>%
  mutate(match_duration_category = case_when(
    minutes < 90 ~ "Short",
    minutes >= 90 & minutes <= 180 ~ "Medium",
    minutes > 180 ~ "Long",
    TRUE ~ "Unknown"
  ))
matches <- matches %>%
  mutate(federer_favorite_surface = ifelse(surface == "Grass", "Yes", "No"))
top_rivals <- c("Rafael Nadal", "Novak Djokovic", "Andy Murray")

matches <- matches %>%
  mutate(against_top_rival = ifelse(loser_name %in% top_rivals | winner_name %in% top_rivals, "Yes", "No"))

Using mutate(), I added four new columns to the dataset:

win_percentage Measures Federers ranking dominance in matches.

match_duration_category Classifies matches as Short, Medium, or Long based on duration.

federer_favorite_surface Identifies if a match was played on his preferred surface (Grass) based in the Win Rate by Surface graph.

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.
